{{POV|date=September 2018}} {{BLP sources|date=March 2017}} {{Use British English|date=October 2012}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}} {{Infobox officeholder |order=16th [[Mayor of Karachi]] | image = |imagesize =221x221px | caption = |predecessor = Hakeem Muhammad Ahsan |successor = H.M. Habibullah Paracha |predecessor1 = S.M.Taufiq |successor1 = [[Abdul Sattar Afghani]] |order1= 22nd [[Mayor of Karachi]] | birth_date = 15 August 1895 | birth_place = [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]] | death_date = December 1972 | death_place = | spouse = | children = | parents = | residence = [[Karachi]], [[Sindh]], [[Pakistan]] |alma_mater = | party = Congress before partition after 1945 Pakistan Muslim league. | occupation = [[Politician]] |religion = [[Islam]] | image_size = |term_start=Apr 1951 |term_end=January 10, 1953 |term_start1=May 1961 |term_end1=October 1962 }}
'''Khan Bahadur Allah Bakhsh Gabol''' ({{lang-ur|''' خان بهادرالله بخش گبول '''}}) (15 August 1895 – December 1972) was a political leader of the 20th century and an exponent of the [[Pakistan]] Movement from [[Sindh]] [http://www.dawn.com/2007/08/27/fea.htm]. He owned a considerable portion of land in Karachi, including the area of Lea Market and the stretch of land where Safoora Goth, Abdullah Gabol Goth, Chutta Khan Goth and Gadap now exist. He also possessed the land where [[Gabol Town]] and [[Jinnah International Airport]] are now located. Allah Bakhsh Gabol was the son of a landlord Khudadad Khan Gabol, and the grandfather of [[Nabil Gabol]][https://web.archive.org/web/20080322231430/http://www.thenews.com.pk/updates.asp?id=40902].
== Political life == Gabol was the first Deputy Speaker of the [[Sindh Assembly]], after the imposition of Government of [[India]] Act 1935 [https://web.archive.org/web/20080430182140/http://www.pap.gov.pk/pro-ass/sindh.htm]. He defeated Haji Sir Abdullah Haroon in 1937 in the first election after [[Sindh]] was separated from Bombay. He was also twice elected the Mayor of the then [[Karachi]] Municipal Corporation in 1953 and 1962. It is now the Karachi Metropolitan Corporation. [http://www.dawn.com/2006/07/24/top10.htm]. Due to his outstanding status, he was awarded the title of Khan Bahadur by the [[British Empire]] and after the [[Pakistan Movement|independence]] of [[Pakistan]] in 1947, he was awarded the Sitara i Imtiaz by President Ayub Khan in 1966. Thus he was considered to be an influential politician of Karachi of his times.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sindhudesh.com/gmsyed/case/saeen-book1-part1.htm |title=The Case of Sindh – G.M. Syed’s deposition in court (Part 1) |access-date=1 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012100942/http://www.sindhudesh.com/gmsyed/case/saeen-book1-part1.htm |archive-date=12 October 2007 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
==Baloch League== Karachi is not only the cradle of the modern [[Baloch people|Balochi]] literary movement, but also the centre to uphold the modern Baloch political trends. Simultaneous with formation of the [[Anjuman Khudam-ul-Quran|Anjuman]], the Baloch literary class in Karachi formed a nationalist organisation, called the Baloch League. Gholam Mohammad Noor ud-Din, educated from [[Bombay]], was appointed as its president. The other members of its leadership were: Waja Omar Bakhsh Sabera, a famous merchant, Maolavi Mohammad Osman, Mehrab Khan, Issa Khan, Maolavi Abdul Samad Sarbazi, Khan Sahib Osman, Pir Bakhsh Shahdad and Gabol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balochistaninfo.com/200604/BalochNationalismitsOriginandDevelopment.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-08-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071008130816/http://www.balochistaninfo.com/200604/BalochNationalismitsOriginandDevelopment.pdf |archivedate=8 October 2007 }}</ref> In its annual conference in 1930 the League condemned Magasi's imprisonment and openly demanded his immediate release from the British authorities. In the late 1930s, after his graduation from Aligarh University, the nationalist leader, [[Ghaus Bakhsh Bizenjo]] also joined the League.
