{{Infobox language family |name=Katembri–Taruma |acceptance=proposed |region=[[Brazil]], [[Guyana]] |familycolor=American |family=Proposed [[language family]] |child1=[[Katembri language|Katembrí]] |child2=[[Taruma language|Taruma]] |glotto=NA }}
'''Katembri–Taruma''' is a [[language family]] proposed by [[Terrence Kaufman|Kaufman]] (1990) that links two extinct or critically endangered languages of South America, Katembrí also known as Mirandela of [[Bahia|Bahia State]], Brazil<ref>Métraux, A. (1951). Une nouvelle langue Tapuya de la région de Bahia, (Brésil). Journal de la Société de Americanistes. 40: 51-58 </ref>, and Taruma also known as Taruamá of Brazil and Guyana. The proposal is not repeated in Campbell & Grondona (2012).
