{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{italic title}} {{redirect|Governance of China|the governing body|Government of China}} {{Infobox book | name = The Governance of China | image = Governance of China.png | image_caption = English copies of ''The Governance of China'' | author = [[Xi Jinping]] | editors = [[State Council Information Office]], [[Central Policy Research Office|Party Literature Research Office]] of [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|CPCCC]]), [[China International Publishing Group]] | title_orig = 习近平谈治国理政 | country = [[Mainland China]] | language = Simplified Chinese, English, Arabic, French, German, Japanese, Portuguese, Russian, Spanish, others | genre = Politics | publisher = [[Foreign Languages Press]] | pub_date = 2014, 2017 | english_pub_date = 2014, 2017 | media_type = Print (Hardcover, Paperback) | pages = 515 (V.I), 620 (V.II) | website = {{cite web |url=http://www.china.org.cn/china/node_7214554.htm |title=china.org.cn}} | isbn = 978-7-119-09023-8 | isbn_note = (Vol. I) }}
{{Xi Jinping sidebar}}
'''''The Governance of China''''' is a Chinese political book in two volumes written by [[Xi Jinping]], the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|general secretary]] of the [[Communist Party of China]] and current [[President of the People's Republic of China|president]] of the [[People's Republic of China]]. The first volume was published in 2014, and the second volume was published in 2017. The work is a collection of several dozen speeches and writings by Xi on a variety of topics, which present an official [[party line (politics)|party line]] for China's development in the 21st century.<ref>{{cite book |last=Xi |first=Jinping |title=The Governance of China (Volume I) |publisher=Foreign Languages Press |date=2014 |isbn= 978-7-119-09057-3}} English paperback edition.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Xi |first=Jinping |title=The Governance of China (Volume II) |publisher=Foreign Languages Press |date=2017 |isbn=9787119111636}} English paperback edition.</ref> In these respects, ''Governance of China'' is a literary successor to [[Mao Zedong]]'s ''[[Quotations from Chairman Mao Tse-tung]]''.<ref name="timeslit">{{cite web |url=https://www.the-tls.co.uk/articles/public/little-red-book-big-white-one/ |title=From the Little Red Book to the Big White one |last=Wasserstrom |first=Jeffrey |date=15 May 2018 |website=[[Times Literary Supplement]]}}</ref>
==Synopsis==
''Governance of China'' consists of 178 pieces, organized thematically into 35 chapters.{{efn|Volume I has 79 pieces spread across 18 chapters,<ref name="cn1">{{cite web |url=http://www.china.org.cn/china/2018-01/29/content_50344828.htm |title=First volume of Xi's book on governance republished |website=[[China Internet Information Center|china.org.cn]]}}</ref> while volume II has 99 pieces spread across 17 chapters.<ref name="cn2">{{cite web |url=http://www.china.org.cn/china/2014-10/23/content_33849816.htm |title=About the Book |website=''china.org.cn''}}</ref>}} Both of the work's volumes were edited by three entities: the [[State Council Information Office]], the [[Central Policy Research Office|Party Literature Research Office]] (of the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|CPC Central Committee]]), and the [[China International Publishing Group]].<ref name="govpubI">''Governance I'', publisher's note.</ref><ref name="govpubII">''Governance II'', publisher's note.</ref> The volumes are also interspersed with photography of Xi, depicting him "at work and in daily life".<ref name="govpubI" />{{efn|Volume I includes 45 photographs of Xi,<ref name="govpubI" /> while volume II includes 29 photographs of him.<ref name="govpubII" />}}
The text articulates [[Xi Jinping Thought]], Xi's [[political philosophy]], as it relates to large-scale political issues concerning China including economics, [[Politics of China|domestic politics]], [[Foreign relations of China|international relations]], infrastructure, technology, environmentalism, [[China's peaceful rise|peaceful co-existence]], and the [[People's Liberation Army|military]]. Volume I also contains an appendix which is a political biography of Xi.
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center; background-color: LightYellow;" ! colspan="3"|Volume I !! colspan="3"|Volume II |- ! Chapter !! Pieces !! Title !! Chapter !! Pieces !! Title |- | 1 | 4 | [[Socialism with Chinese Characteristics]] | 1 | 8 | Socialism with Chinese Characteristics and the Chinese Dream |- | 2 | 7 | The [[Chinese Dream]] | 2 | 4 | A Moderately Prosperous Society in All Respects |- | 3 | 5 | All-round and Deeper-level Reform | 3 | 6 | Deeper Reform |- | 4 | 5 | Economic Development | 4 | 4 | Rule of Law |- | 5 | 3 | [[Chinese_law#Rule_of_law|Rule of Law]] | 5 | 12 | Governing the Party with Strict Discipline |- | 6 | 6 | Culturally Advanced China | 6 | 3 | New Development Concepts |- | 7 | 7 | Social Undertakings | 7 | 8 | The New Normal of Economic Development |- | 8 | 3 | Ecological Progress | 8 | 5 | Socialist Democracy |- | 9 | 3 | National Defense | 9 | 9 | Cultural Confidence |- | 10 | 5 | "[[One Country, Two Systems]]" | 10 | 8 | The Wellbeing of the People |- | 11 | 5 | [[China's peaceful rise|Peaceful Development]] | 11 | 5 | Beautiful China |- | 12 | 3 | New Model of Major-country Relations | 12 | 4 | Military Development |- | 13 | 3 | Neighborhood Diplomacy | 13 | 3 | One Country, Two Systems |- | 14 | 3 | Cooperation with Developing Countries | 14 | 3 | China's Diplomacy as a Major Country |- | 15 | 6 | Multilateral Relations | 15 | 9 | Peaceful Development and Cooperation with Other Countries |- | 16 | 4 | Close Ties with the People | 16 | 4 | The [[Belt and Road Initiative]] |- | 17 | 3 | [[Anti-corruption campaign under Xi Jinping|Combat Corruption]] | 17 | 4 | A Community of Shared Future |- | 18 | 4 | [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|The CPC Leadership]] | colspan="3"| |- | colspan="2"|Appendix | Man of the People | colspan="3"| |}
==Release==
Both volumes of ''Governance of China'' were formally presented to western audiences at the [[London Book Fair]] upon their releases,<ref name="timeslit" /><ref name="gcd">{{cite web |url=http://www.dialogue.global-china.org/cms.php?artid=1041&catid=701 |title=Helping with the book launch of ''The Governance of China by Xi Jinping'' |website=Global China Dialogue |year=2015}}</ref> and both volumes have been translated into other major languages apart from Chinese, including English, Arabic, French, German, Japanese, Portuguese, Russian, and Spanish.<ref name="telegraph">{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/world/china-watch/culture/xi-jinpings-book-on-policy/ |title=Influence of Xi Jinping book spreads with editions in more languages |date=24 May 2017 |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]; [[China Daily]]}}</ref><ref name="gbtimes">{{cite web |url=https://gbtimes.com/second-volume-of-xi-jinpings-book-launched-in-eight-foreign-languages |title=Second volume of Xi Jinping's book launched in eight foreign languages |last=Jessup |first=Catherine |date=11 April 2018 |website=gbtimes}}</ref>
Digital versions of volume I in Chinese and English are available on digital trade platforms including [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[OverDrive, Inc.|OverDrive]], CNPeReading and iReader.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-07/06/c_137306646.htm|title=Chinese, English editions of Xi's book on governance of country go digital|website=[[Xinhua News Agency|Xinhua]]|date=2018-07-06 }}</ref>
==Reception==
Reviews of ''Governance of China'' have been mixed, including positive reception from Chinese officials,<ref name="ciic">{{cite web |url=http://www.china.org.cn/china/2017-12/22/content_50120289.htm |title=Wang Huning stresses importance of Xi's second book on governance |date=22 December 2017 |website=''china.org.cn''}}</ref> measured praise from non-Chinese leaders,<ref name="economist">{{cite web |url=https://www.economist.com/china/2018/04/26/xi-jinpings-new-blockbuster-is-getting-a-hard-sell |title=Xi Jinping's new blockbuster is getting a hard sell |date=26 April 2018 |website=[[The Economist]]}}</ref> and negative reviews in Western media, where the work is sometimes regarded as propaganda.<ref name="foreign">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/02/05/we-read-xi-jinpings-book-so-you-dont-have-to/ |title=We Read Xi Jinping's Book So You Don't Have To |last=Allen-Ebrahimian |first=Bethany |date=5 February 2015 |website=[[Foreign Policy]]}}</ref><ref name="techaeris">{{cite web |url=https://techaeris.com/2014/12/08/mark-zuckerberg-reportedly-buying-governance-china-employees/ |title=Mark Zuckerberg Reportedly Buying 'The Governance of China' For Employees |last=Hernandez |first=Alex |date=8 December 2014 |website=Techaeris}}</ref> Facebook CEO [[Mark Zuckerberg]] is reported to have read the book, and to have ordered copies for the company's employees. Zuckerberg's interest in the book has been interpreted as a [[Vested interest (communication theory)|vested interest]]; Facebook is [[Internet censorship in China|blocked in China]], and if the block were lifted, the potential result would be a dramatic increase in Facebook's userbase.<ref name="techaeris" />
Although Chinese media have reported global circulation numbers for the book's volumes on the order of several million copies,<ref name="telegraph" /><ref name="economist" /> Western media have also reported very low sales numbers for the work in Western countries.<ref name="economist" /><ref name="time">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/3827869/china-president-xi-jinping-book-bestseller/ |title=Is Chinese President Xi Jinping's Book of Speeches Really a Best Seller? |last=Beech |first=Hannah |date=20 April 2015 |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref>{{efn|"There may not be very many readers outside China. The publisher claims the second volume has a global circulation of 13m. But, according to Scott Morton of Nielsen Bookscan, a data provider, fewer than 100 copies of the English-language version of the second volume have actually been sold in Britain since it was published in November. Sales are slightly higher in Australia, at 124. The first volume has not performed much better: 588 copies in Britain and 430 in Australia. It is likely that freebies of both volumes hugely exceed the number of copies sold to individuals. Finding foreigners who have actually read Xi’s magnum opus is about as easy as finding thigh-slapping jokes in it."<ref name="economist" />}}
